<article>
    <h1>THE SINGAPURA AEROSPACE CLUB</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201122/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-22"><time>2020-11-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Where: Sele­tar Aerospace Park, 2 The Oval; open: 10.30am to 10.30pm daily</p>
    <p>Info: Call 6974-8001 or go to www.face­book.com/ thesin­ga­pu­r­a­club</p>
    <p>The Singapura Aerospace Club is the lat­est ad­di­tion to the Sele­tar Aerospace Park life­style en­clave, which is home to the likes of the pop­u­lar Wheeler’s Es­tate and The Sum­mer­house, as well as new French restau­rant 5 by Sans Fa­con.</p>
    <p>Lounge out­doors and watch the chil­dren frolic at the play­ground, or dine in­doors in the cosy, home-style set­ting, com­plete with avi­a­tion-re­lated an­tiques.</p>
    <p>The colo­nial bun­ga­low’s old-school charm meets the fu­ture with a ro­botic barista arm that whips up drinks at the Robo-Bar – in part­ner­ship with Ra­tio cafe and lounge, which is by Sin­ga­porean com­pany Ross Dig­i­tal.</p>
    <p>Ra­tio launched ear­lier this month next to co-work­ing space JustCo at The Cen­tre­point.</p>
    <p>The ro­botic arm is said to en­sure con­sis­tency for drinks such as cof­fee, mock­tails and cock­tails.</p>
    <p>Pair your bev­er­ages with light bites, in­clud­ing chicken or mut­ton sa­tay (from $12.80 for 10 sticks); house-made ngoh hi­ang ($12.80); ad­dic­tive fish sticks ($10.80) or keropok lekor which orig­i­nates from Tereng­ganu.</p>
    <p>Mains in­clude cray­fish char kway teow ($16.80), beef ren­dang nasi lemak ($16.80) and a range of tan­doori plat­ters.</p>
    <p>Bar­be­cue pits are avail­able for out­door cook­ing with the fam­ily.</p>
    <p>They are avail­able only on Fri­days, eve of pub­lic hol­i­days and pub­lic hol­i­days (book three days ahead).</p>
    <p>Not sure what to grill? Or­der the Singapura Plat­ter (from $88 for two to three peo­ple), which</p>
    <p>in­cludes raw items such as lamb shoul­der, chicken wings, prawns and otah.</p>
    <p>The Singapura Aerospace Club’s other out­lets are in Haji Lane and Lit­tle In­dia.</p>
    <p>C CAFE</p>
    <p>Where: 477 Joo Chiat Road; open: 8am to 6pm daily Info: www.face­book.com/ccafe.sg</p>
    <p>What sets this min­i­mal­ist cafe apart is the el­e­ment of magic – in the menu shaped like a deck of cards and with walls ac­cented with card dec­o­ra­tions. The own­ers also per­form ta­ble-side magic tricks on week­ends or on re­quest if they are not too busy.</p>
    <p>Of­ten filled with yo­gis, ex­pats and stu­dents, the bustling cafe serves dishes such as av­o­cado on sour­dough toast ($18); Break­fast of Cham­pi­ons ($24) which in­cludes pork sausage, ba­con, poached eggs and mush­rooms; and Tasty Toasties ($18) – go for the leg ham with house-made tomato rel­ish.</p>
    <p>Other op­tions in­clude sal­ads (from $15) and sides such as spam fries ($10) and truf­fle fries ($12).</p>

